HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 1248
By Reneau
A RESOLUTION to honor and commend the Association of
Environmental and Engineering Geologists on
the occasion of its sixty-ninth annual meeting.
WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this General Assembly should honor those
exemplary organizations that provide leadership, advocacy, and applied research in the
sciences; and
WHEREAS, one such commendable organization is the Association of Environmental
and Engineering Geologists, which contributes to its members' professional success and the
public welfare by providing leadership, advocacy, and applied research in the fields of
environmental and engineering geology; and
WHEREAS, the Association of Environmental and Engineering Geologists was founded
in 1957 and later incorporated on May 7, 1963, in California; and
WHEREAS, since its founding, the Association of Environmental and Engineering
Geologists has grown to include twenty-six chapters, including one in Nashville; and
WHEREAS, members of the Association of Environmental and Engineering Geologists
as practitioners in the fields of environmental and engineering geology provide benefit to the
public by assessing natural hazards, protecting the environment, remediating contamination,
and supporting the design and construction of engineered works such as roads, bridges,
tunnels, and dams; and
WHEREAS, the Association of Environmental and Engineering Geologists has chosen to
host its annual meeting in Chattanooga on September 13-19, 2026; and
WHEREAS, this is the first annual meeting that the Association of Environmental and
Engineering Geologists has held in the State of Tennessee; now, therefore,
HJR1248
016782
- 1 -

BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor and commend the Association of Environmental and Engineering
Geologists on the occasion of its sixty-ninth annual meeting. We welcome those attending the
meeting to enjoy all that Tennessee has to offer and salute the organization and its members for
their efforts to uphold sound principles of scientific inquiry with respect to the study and
evaluation of geologic processes and the interaction of people with the earth and its natural
environment.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
